          Woke up this morning to find out that the job I've been wanting down at school has been filled by someone else, which is quite a shame, because working for Apple would've been incredibly fun. Oh well, guess I'll have to settle for something much less exciting, because income is necessary. As long as I don't have to work in food, everything will be okay. I could even deal with retail, if it came to that.<br /><br />But enough of personal frustration over opportunities missed. It's time for some good ol' fashioned music recommendation (which I'll be doing a lot of, I think).<br /><br />"Frou Frou" is a very unique electronic pop duo from the U.K., composed of young chanteuse Imogen Heap and world-famous producer Guy Sigsworth (Madonna, Björk). Together, they've crafted a delectable 45 minutes of perfectly formed electronic beats and orchestras that back Immi's immediately identifiable voice, as she sings obtusely about love, loss, hope, regret, jealousy, and everything in between. The first track, "Let Go," was used by Zach Braff in the <a href="http://www.apple.com/trailers/fox_searchlight/garden_state/" target="_new">trailer</a> for his upcoming movie "Garden State." It's a good starter into Frou Frou's distinct style, but only one facet of a varied and beautiful album. The closest band to Frou Frou that I've heard would be Massive Attack, but less down-tempo and dark, and with more of a happy, pop sensibility. Oh, and in case you're wondering, "frou frou" is the French sound of rustling silk petticoats.<br /><br />More to come...<br />
